{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Basset Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. And - I remember - going down buying a - a camera there half a crown camera, the two plates, and Mr Whitford said if I take the photograph he would take it - he would develop it free. And - anyhow - we waited until Monday 
but already the - the camera was used, my brother used the first plate and then he - he took a photo of Sammy Whear. Sammy Whear was a noted - noted person in Camborne them days at driving cattle and so on and he - he told Sammy - he'd have to not shave f
or a week. So he could come out better in the picture. So he - he took Sammy - with this beard on to send to a - a sister in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}America{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. Anyhow - my brother, he was a bit of a songwriter and composer evidently, he wrote a bit of a - poetry. He said, what's the
 use of having a face if you don't know how to use 'en, just as well to go away and drown the thing or lose it. I'll used mine as a doormat or I'll put my beard out sign, the finest thing in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}England{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} is a face like mine. That was put in the window for attraction, but Sammy didn't mind. I don't know if you want that there or not.
