\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 When you had a birthday would it be different from any other day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 
No, I don't think so, mind - I remember - mother giving me a ha'penny I think for a jelly, going down the shop and - buying a jelly, you'd get a ha - a jelly for a ha'penny then. Then - have some hot water there
 and make this here - jelly. I also - I remember going down for treacle, make - bit of clidgy, used to call it - anyhow, you could get a ha'porth of treacle then, you go down the shop, they had it all loose then, and got quite a bit for a ha'penny. And th
en you make this here clidgey, on top of the kitchen range.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Did you have any guests to tea or celebrate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 
No, only - when - the relatives from the Lanner area, of course - mother still had - had two brothers down there. They used to come across to
 the Camborne Feast, I know one uncle did, and he came here in very bad weather one time and he - was so bad with the snow that he couldn't face the weather. And he borrowed a - a closed in conveyance from a Mr Mills, St Day I think, but he came to the Ca
m
borne Feast, he - he said he wouldn't miss Camborne Feast for anything. Yes, Camborne Feast was a - a great thing in Camborne in them days, and - most everybody - used to have special - food and things for that - chicken or something like that. I remember
 going down by Union Street Camborne on the - just before dinner time and smell the different stuff coming out the - smells from the different houses and that. Everybody had a bit of special then. Of course my brother said a fellow came home from 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Africa{\*\xmlclose} for the Camborne Feast one, he - he walked - hitchhiked I believe most of the way. 'Course - yes, the Camborne Feast was - was around the eleventh of November.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 
Can you remember anything you did with your mother or father together on Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 
Oh well - we always had - little special - things for Christmas, and I remember - Santa Claus we were told - all had to fill up their stockings in them days with - oranges and apples and sweets and things like that, but not many toys them days. But - of c
o
urse we had a lot of carol singing Christmas, and - there was a lot of - choirs going around, little parties going around singing carols and - I know my mother used to give 'em all lemonade and this here saffron cake when they come. I don't know if they e
ver - ever - have a good old bus top but they did.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Did you have any musical instruments in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Oh - we had a organ there I think, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Who played the organ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Well I think my eldest sister was the only one that could play the orga
n properly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Was there anybody in the family who sang?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 
Well we were all very good singers. I know mother was a great singer, I know - my father and all the others are very good singers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Did you ever make music together as a family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Wel
l I suppose we did, I don't remember a lot about that. Yes - singing, well, I do remember - when we was at Tregaforran or near Tregajorran there, that's - when we went up to - to that part to live, we had a organ there and we had a piano there. Anyhow - S
u
nday mornings, the brother and me were there singing these here Corn - the Old - American ballads and that you know. Harmonising and - I would play little bits on the organ, he would play the principle part, and - then mother would say, they're now coming
 
back from Tregaforran chapel. Sing something a bit more quieter. So then we used to sing a few hymns then, and we - mother said, some crowd outside now, listening. One song we had - I'm coming, my head is bending low. A lot of the old minstrel songs we us
e
d to sing then, but I can't remember them all now, but I know the - very nice old songs to harmonise with. But mother didn't think that was proper for the chapel people, so then of course we had to - sing these few hymns. Well that would keep the crowd th
ere for quite a while. And then - when we had - finished like then of course they would - move off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Did your parents play any games with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 No, no, I don't think so, not in particular.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Were there books in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Well there may ha
ve been - may have been lots of books there, of course - my brother, he was great reader, eldest brother. And - of course they always had the Bible, the family Bible, big family Bible we had. And we've still got that I think. And the - the public library 
o
f course - I remember when the foundation stone was laid, for that library, and - mother - mother and father - were there - talking about this here library and then - the - Mr Bennett the photographer wanted to know to know if he could fix his camera up i
n
 the - in the bedroom window there, bay window, to take the foundation - laying of the foundation stone. And if you - if you allow me to put the camera up there I'll take your family group free. So - anyhow, he took the photograph and - and - then - mothe
r
 said, well she didn't like the photograph very much. So Mr Bennett said, you'll look better if you had a cup of tea first. But I remember going over there - going over there, at the library when it was opened for books and - my brother, he'd be - he'd be
 all the time reading of course I - used to read a few books I know, 'cos Conan Doyle's is a great - attraction them days, in the - they were interesting books as far as I was concerned.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Did you have any newspapers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Oh yes, we had the - the loca
l paper of course was the Cornish Post. That was - a weekly paper. That was always there but - but no other Cornish papers I don't think, not in them days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Any magazines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Not that I remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Do you remember father or mother reading aloud to you or to each other?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 
Well I - I - I've got an idea they did but I haven't got a very clear recollection of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Do you remember them reading?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 No. No, I don't really. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Do you remember a funeral in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Of course I rem
ember - when my father died. Of course - we all went to the funeral and of course in the - the uncle down at Lanner he came there and his wife and - both - quite a big number attended the funeral. I remember - going to the funeral myself. We all went to t
he funeral. And of course we had to dress in black in them days and I think I went to Vivians at Camborne to get a - a black suit, for the funeral. Everybody was in black.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Did anyone outside the family attend?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Oh - yes, it was a very big funeral,
 because he was well respected in the town. And a - a lot of the principle people and all were at - at this funeral. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Lot{\*\xmlclose} of well known people, I - of course I can't remember their names exactly now.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Was it a walking funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Yes, walking funera
l. Well there was - there may have been a - a couple of carriages in the front, but walking funeral as far as I know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Service in the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 
His - the service at the primitive chapel, 'course he was a great man at the chapel. He was superintendent of the - Sunday school there. And - the funeral service was at the Primitive Chapel then he was buried at the - the cemetery at Camborne.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 As a child were you taken out visiting neighbours, friends or relations?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 No, only - I remember going to 
- to Lanner in the summer - summer holidays it was. That's Joshua and me, and - we went down to - Uncle - Joshua Williams and at - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Cam{\*\xmlclose}
 - at Lanner. He kept a grocers shop and bit of a farm there. And - we - went from Camborne from bus, Symons bus it was then, and - we went to Redruth, that - that bus went on to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}
}Truro{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Then we had to change buses there at Redruth and get on the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Falmouth{\*\xmlclose}
 bus and I remember the - Mr Symons having all particulars given to him, what to do at Redruth, handing us over - make sure everything's all right on the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Falmouth{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose} bus. I remember going down there and I believe he had - we had these straw hats them time, chippers I think they used to call them. Anyhow - I remember being dressed up special for that occasion. 'Cos me uncle, he had
 this here grocers shop down there and bit of a farm, and then - 'cos that's my brother's - mother's brother that was, and - he also - used to buy a lot of this here old property down there, and - he'd do a bit of lime washing and do it up a bit and then 
he'd let 'em out to different people but - the conditions was - if you - live in his house you had to buy all your groceries there in the shop. So to finish up with he had a good bit of Lanner property there, and a good many customers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Did you visit your father's brother there as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 
No. No. Of course I remember the - my - my father's sister, Aunt Maria Ann Morcomb, she kept a - a - a day school there, a penny school, penny a week it used to be, she couldn't read or write, and - anyhow - her hus
band, Tom Morcomb, he used to - be out in the back yard there with a big shovel with a hole in the centre, and he used to keep going around with this here handleless shovel. He used to gind down the tin of of this here stone they tell me, and they used to
 
make a living that way. I don't know how - how much that was, but he told me that - they've gone down Tresavean, this here mine, he said, well, he said, that's a good job, he said, they go up Penstruthal where I get my tin stone from I shall have no - no 
t
in stone, good job they're gone down there, he said. I remember that. And she had a spy glass there. And - oh a very long powerful glass, look out at all the scenery around there, and - she said, Telfer, when I die you shall have spy glass. But I never go
t
 him. Don't know where it is now. 'Course - father' brother, John Blewett, he used to work at - Cornish Pump, at the line I believe, and the Cornish pump was very successful. More successful, they tried this electric pumps but they had a lot of trouble wi
t
h 'em, well anyhow this here Cornish pump would pump almost anything, stones and everything. And then - he went from the - the mine at East Pool to Severn Tunnel, to work the Cornish pump there. That was in - operation at this in the Severn Tunnel. I don'
t know how long it was in operation, but anyhow, then he went to London, to Waltham Abbey Water Works, to work the Cornish pump and then - he worked up to manager, he was a manager of Waltham Abby Water Works.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Did you ever go out with just father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 
Oh well - only that - that - when he took the band concert or something like that you know. No particular place, I - of course we always went out together, mother - and - father, little walks and so on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Were you taken shopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Oh yes - yes, 
I think we went - to Vivians - for drapery and like that with mother, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Do you remember any other outings with your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 No, no particular - outings. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 On Bank Holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 No, of course - my parents didn't - didn't go away very
 much but of course - at Camborne - in them days - Good Friday was a big day. That was a - outing at North Cliffs, used to - go down there, pick limpets and wash your feet once a year. That's a - annual do that was. And I remember - my sister - eldest sis
t
er, no, not the eldest sister, no, Feodore, she going down to a shop in Camborne, a furniture shop used to let out these here - chair - push chairs with very high wheels. And so much a hour. And - I remember - she went down to hire one of these here - pus
h chairs and pushing me off to North Cliffs, I remember that. I think used to pay threepence, was it threepence for half a day I believe that - push chair. Yes. 'Course - we used to have a outing every year at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Carbis{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bay{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, Sunday school outing - Sunday schoo
l outing. They used to go by train, that was a lovely treat that was, going by train to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Carbis{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bay{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}. I think it used to cost sixpence ha'penny. I also remember - my father going to visit - my eldest sister, she was a manageress at a shop in Veryan and - our
 pony was - wasn't that particular big so she - he hired a - a - what they call a cob, a much bigger pony, at Camborne, and - we set off Sunday morning from Camborne, this here - jingle, to go to Veryan. When we got down to King Harriet Passage the farrie
r
 had just finished the - the journey he used to do in in the mornings and - we saw him going into the house there. My father went and seen him and asked him if he'd tip him to take us across, special trip and he took us across. And then - we got into Very
a
n, and I remember going in the field there, they had a lovely - kitchen garden, going down and picking the peas and one thing and another. Anyhow, going back, we had to come back the same night, it was a long journey just one day and going back - we - we 
g
ot across the ferry all right, but then - when we got - to Tuckingmill, the - the toll gates there then, and - the toll gate was closed. And my father had to go in and wake up the fellow in the - in the tollgate place, to open this gate for us to go throu
gh, I think it was a penny to go through and - of course that there old toll house is still there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 
Apart from the holiday with your brother at Lanner did you ever go away for a holiday any other time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 No, we - not that I remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Could you tell me how you spent Saturdays in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 
Well - of course - I used to attend football or cricket, whatever the season was. I was very fond of sport. 'Course I - I played a good bit of football when I was a boy, and I remember in the back - roa
d playing football, with the schoolboys and that and - I scored a try and I broke my leg. I - I just scored the try and the bloke jumped on top of me back and I broke my thigh. I remember - that wasn't running just after school, it was - half past seven b
e
fore they set the leg and then - they used to put big weights on the bottom of the bed - wooden - like a wooden cross business with weights on, and if you go to sleep, my eldest brother used to put more weights on to keep the - the leg from getting shore.
 
And - anyhow I - I got - after a long time was - on crutches, then a stick, I went down to the recreation ground, and the boys in there playing and - of course I joined in again. Dropped this stick down on the grass there and - when I got back - got back 
t
he stick was gone. So I had to tell mother a yarn now, tell her that I was - laying down, went to sleep, and when I woke up the stick was gone. So when I went home with that yarn, and it was too late, somebody had been there, there was no use saying that 
t
o her, oh you've been playing football again. Oh I used to play - just ordinary games like marbles and kite flying, that was a very popular thing, making the kites and so on. And I - it was - one was knuckle fists I think it was, one - marble game, I don'
t remember all the names now but I know we had a - a chaser game, we used to play along the water tables going to school, remember that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 How about Sundays? What happened on Sundays, how did you spend your Sundays?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Oh well - when I was young my fa
ther was alive, we had to go to Sunday school then. Of course later - I - I got in with a lot of boys and that, friends and that and - we - joined the - the Church - Church Lads Brigade, and - the Lads Brigade then was up at Troon, and Mr Marriot, he was 
t
he curate, I think he - been in the regular Army one time. He was oh a fine chap, plenty of money I believe he had too, anyhow, we had a fine brigade, bugle band and whatever, and we had a - a first camp there. We went to Lyme Regis for a camp, and the fi
r
st night we were washed out, the tents were all blown down, went to the school for the night. And after that it was all right. Well anyhow - nearly all the brigade went, I think it was - Tommy Eustace, he was the Lieutenant I believe Tommy was, he - he ha
d
 a - a paint - carpenter - local carpenter I think, a painter and so on and - Mr Marriot he sent him - a wire back to Troon to bring down the rest of the Brigade. Well Tommy arrived with two others, I think he had - don't think he had more than two - thre
e
 at the most and when he saw our Brigade going down to this train Tommy started running down the platform, 'cos he had his sword and his Sam Brown, and the sword - 'cos Tommy wasn't very tall - sword tripped Tommy up, Tommy went flying down the platform. 
Anyhow it all turned out right, he had - the bugle band to play us back.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Did you have different clothes to wear on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 
Oh yes, I think - we - had to dress up a bit different on a Sunday, 'course - during the week, mean to say, didn't mind w
hat you had on in a sense, though we were always tidy and respectable. But then - we were stopped from playing football or any other sport on Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Did your parents think it wrong to work or play on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Yes, oh yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Did your parents attend a place of worship or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 
Yes, when my father was alive we always went to - to chapel, the Primitive chapel in mornings and evenings. And of course he was Superintendant of the - the Sunday school. And then of course - we had our tea trea
ts you know, and - I know my father, he had a band at Lanner them days, he had two cousins there and of course - used to have a meeting to select what band they have, they could put offers in, and - and prices so - anyhow father were very anxious to have 
L
anner band because having these two cousins there. Anyway, he got the - they booked Lanner band. Anyhow, that time - every - every - I believe every school in Camborne, every - every - every church or chapel had their treat on - Whit Monday. The church, t
h
ey didn't go round the town though, they - played a part of the town then back into the vicarage but the others all went round Trelawarren Street, follow the band, and - I believe there was a - a band up Black Rock, so - my brother told me. There's some b
rothers went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}America{\*\xmlclose} and they come home with six of these lovely uniforms, like they used to wear in - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}
America{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and the - the guards out there. Anyhow, they bought these uniforms and - Black Rock band was down at Camborne, I don't remember that, remember 
my brother talking about it. They said they're the best - best dressed band of the whole lot. Didn't play very much but they - 'cos - when the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Cam{\*\xmlclose}
 - when the Lanner band was out at Camborne I remember my father - had to pay 'em off, so - they kept on playi
ng, it was about seven, half past seven, still playing. Oh, he told 'em you - you can finish up now bosy, you've done a good job. Well anyhow they kept on playing and - eventually they said we - we couldn't play God Save the Queen, we had to wait 'til eve
rybody went out.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Did you go to Sunday school or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Were there any other social activities organised by the church or chapel?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 
Well they had bazaars I believe, that sort of thing you know. Oh they did have a Band of Hope, I may have belonged to that, I'm not quite sure.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Did you belong to the choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 
No. No. Not until I - only the church, only the - school choir. I was in the choir there. I was thought to have a good voice, so they said, and - anyhow - every - eve
ry year used to have a - a school concert, and - the - the - the headmaster, Mr Davies, he was a musical man, and of course he had to - all these here people in to - to sing so he could - judge whether they're good enough for the choir. If he touched any 
o
f the boys on the back, they had to stop singing and go back to the classroom. Well I was touched on the back, I went back. Well I went into my school teacher, Mr Quintrell, Charlie Quintrell, and he said, what are you doing back here? Well, I said, the m
a
ster - touched me on the back. That mean to say I wasn't good enough. Oh nonsense, he said, if you're good enough to sing between - to sing between two and three thousand people at the public rooms you're good enough for the choir. So anyhow, they - I got
 back in the choir again. But I was quite annoyed over that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Were you taught to say prayers at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 We may have done when my father was alive, I don't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Do you remember family prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Well I think my father used to do that. He was very religious was father.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 Was grace said at meals in your family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 
Well - I don't remember, very likely it was, father - I believe my father done it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8480765 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 
Your parents political attitudes, did your father take an interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid675531 JB  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid11556911\charrsid8926906 
Oh yes, yes. Oh yes. Of course my father - mostly through that there - let down at the - at the shop at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Cross Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. He was very - he used to take a good active out, they caught him on the - railway crossing up Camborne, give him a good hiding before h
e got over and ran up the line, and - I had a - a policeman's helmet they picked up there, my brother picked up, with all the top part all battered in, he must have had a good old heavy - bang on the top I suppose. Though I believe the - the troops are go
i
ng to be called in then but - eventually it settled down, but of course electioneering in them days was very rowdy. I think the trouble there was about wages you see. The - the Dolcoath Mine - brought these here miners over of course to work for less mone
y than the Camborne men, that's how the trouble was..
\par }}